div.p:

In dancing, rhythm alone is used without 'harmony';

for even dancing imitates character, emotion, and action,

by rhythmical movement.


For there is no common term we could apply to the

mimes of Sophron and Xenarchus and the Socratic

dialogues on the one hand;


The same thing holds good of Dithyrambs and Nomes;

here too one may portray different types, as Timotheus

and Philoxenus differed in representing their Cyclopes.


The same distinction marks off Tragedy from Comedy;

for Comedy aims at representing men as worse, Tragedy

as better than in actual life.


The additions to the number of 'episodes' 



or acts, and the other accessories of which tradition 

tells, must be taken as already described;


They differ, again, 

in their length: for Tragedy endeavours, as far as 

possible, to confine itself within a single revolution of the sun, or but slightly to exceed this limit;


Again, Tragedy is the imitation of an action; and an 

action implies personal agents, who necessarily possess 

certain distinctive qualities both of character and thought;



for it is by these that we qualify actions themselves, 

and these—thought and character—are the two natural 

causes from which actions spring, and on actions again all success or failure depends.


As the sequel to what has already been said, we must

proceed to consider what the poet should aim at, and

what he should avoid, in constructing his plots;




it merely shocks us. Nor, again, that of a bad man

passing from adversity to prosperity: for nothing can be

more alien to the spirit of Tragedy;


the subdivisions being,—

proof and refutation;



the excitation of the feelings, such as pity, fear, anger, and the like; 

the suggestion of importance or its opposite.


These are distinguished according to the form 

assumed by the mouth and the place where they are 

produced; 

according as they are aspirated or smooth, 

long or short; 

as they are acute, grave, or of an inter- 

mediate tone; 

which inquiry belongs in detail to the 

writers on metre.


A Sentence or Phrase is a composite significant 

sound, some at least of whose parts are in themselves 

significant;


Thus from genus to species, as: 'There lies

my ship'; 

for lying at anchor is a species of lying.


Thus the number of letters in

which nouns masculine and feminine end is the same; 

for ψ and ξ are equivalent to endings in ς.


Yet a style wholly composed of such words is either a

riddle or a jargon; 

a riddle, if it consists of metaphors;

a jargon, if it consists of strange (or rare) words.


and it may even use the Epic metre; 

and, besides, it has as no small part music

and spectacle, through which the pleasures are most vividly felt.
